snippet.textDisplay: These words puchdi wagah to raah Lahore da... Ravi puche Chena toh ki haal Satluj da really raising goosebumps, shows the pain of Punjab.... We were not born then but can feel pain of those Punjabis, the Punjab Maharaja Ranjit Singh created big Punjab which these tyrrant leaders broke into pieces. These Punjabis on both sides really yearn for each other, dying to see the other side of their Punjab, meet the Punjabi brothers living on other side... Why have only Punjabis and Bengalis have to gone through this pain, the two communities which were on the top list in fighting against British got this Separation in return, who still after so many years of independence have this unforgotten pain in their hearts. Wish this sourness between the two countries be finished and we can visit each other's country freely and live in peace and harmony. We have same language, culture, food then why so much bitterness in relations.

snippet.textDisplay: Wow, its my first time listening to this song. That intro was amazing hands down 👏👏👏  on God it gave me goosebumps. I love the subtitles,  thank you. The message is real, (young'ens) please dont forget your traditions and customs. Your culture, food, arts, and garbs are appreciated by everyone. Quick story... my family and I were staying at the Grand Sierra Resort one weekend. I took my six year old nephew to grab some pizza from food court lobby. We were in the elevator heading down as it picked up other guest when suddenly this couple got in. A bride and groom. The bride was killing it with her "indian" gown. Everyone was admiring her when all of the sudden my nephew   whispers to me " uncle, why is there a princess in the elevator?" All you hear are aaaahs and she immediately tears up and turns to him and thanks him with a kiss on the cheek. So, from one brown Hispanic brother to another South east Asian brown bother, May God Bless and protect all Indian/Pakistan/Punjab and everyone else who share that ancestry
